photo.title: Bookplate of the Säfstaholms Bibliothek
photo.description: Bookplate of the Säfstaholms Bibliothek with the initials GTB [=Gustaf Trolle-Bonde] at head of bookplate. Gustaf Trolle-Bonde (1773-1855) "the Blind Excellency" was a patron of the arts and collector of books and paintings. He inherited Säfstaholms in 1797 and rebuilt and redesigned large parts of the estate to house his growing art collection and library. The library was sold in 1920. The estate is now an art museum showcasing Swedish artists from the early 20th century. Established heading (NLS): Trolle-Bonde, Gustaf, 1773-1855 Penn Libraries call number: GrC Ar466 S21 1622 All images from this book

The stamp probably belonged to count Francesco Maria Cardelli (1715-1778), a passionate bibliophile who inherited from his family a library of 4,000 volumes, including many manuscripts of miscellaneous character. Penn Libraries call number: IC6 B7329 617s All images from this book

photo.title: Illustrated bookplate of Harrison Gray Otis
photo.description: Illustrated bookplate of Harrison Gray Otis. Probably not to be identified with Harrison Gray Otis (1837-1917), publisher of the Los Angeles Times. Possibly to be identified with Harrison Gray Otis (1856-1915), great-grandson of Harrison Gray Otis (1765-1848), U.S. Senator from Massachusetts and Mayor of Boston (and nephew of poet Mercy Otis Warren). His father William Church Otis (1831-1889), a Boston wine merchant and auctioneer, married Margaret Sigourney (b. 1833) in 1855; Harrison Gray Otis was the eldest of their five children. He was a member (though not a graduate) of Harvard's class of 1878 and worked briefly in the wool business before retiring. In a report to a Harvard alumni publication in 1901, he mentions that his time thereafter was devoted to the interests of the Boston Athletic Association. He married Louise MacNamara in 1893 and had 2 sons, William Allyne Otis and Harrison Gray Otis (1895-1901), and a daughter, Marghareta Otis. Lewis J. Bird and Co. of Boston auctioned off at least some of "the private library of Harrison Gray Otis including a ... collection of books printed in the first half century of printing" on 6-7 November 1889 and published a sale catalog, whose LC OCLC record gives "Otis, Harrison Gray, ǂd 1856-1915" as the main entry. (Possibly he was clearing out his father's house? William Church Otis died on 13 March 1889, so the timing is suggestive.) Penn Libraries call number: Inc G-499

Lailach identifies this woodcut as a depiction of Asclepius and describes it thus: Im Bild des "Emblema.XLVIII." ist ein alter Mann mit einem langen Bart und einer Kappe auf einer Art Thron dargestellt. Er ist von zwei Vögeln, die einen großen Ring und eine Art Ehrenmünze im Schnabel herbeitragen, und von einem Kamel, Esel und Stier umgeben, die mit Schalen und Fässern herantreten. Sie bringen also ehrende Gaben und Geschenke. Zur Rechten des Mannes sind noch ein Hund mit einem Geldbeutel und eine Katze, die auf unübersehbare Weise ihr Geschäft verrichtet, dargestellt. Der Mann schaut auf den Hund und hebt die rechte Hand mit geöffneter Handfläche dem Tier entgegen. Zur Linken des Mannes liegen hingegen ein Wolf und ein Lamm in Eintracht beieinander.
